But we still need to use %spark magic to have a spark context automatically created for us.

table with all the transformers' signals named *IRISDemo.TransformerSignal* with a column: *Transformer* that 
indicated from which transformer that signal was.

Let's try to build a single data set with all this data joined so we can give a good look at the quality of our data:

paragraphs.title: Reading the data from IRIS

%spark

val df = spark.read.iris("""select 
    Transformer->Code as Transformer,
    TimeOfMeasurement,
    TransformerLoad,
    TopOilTemperature,
    BottomOilTemperature,
    OilVolume,
    MoistureInOil,
    Vibration,
    CAST(VibrationLevel as INTEGER) as VibrationLevel,
    Threat
from 
    IRISDemo.TransformerSignal
""")
    
df.cache()
df.count()

paragraphs.text:

We will have to compensate for this later. 

A simple look at the number of threats compared to normal measurements is enough to see that this is a highly unbalanced data set:

# 3 - Should we use feature selection?

msg.data: 3 - Should we use feature selection?

paragraphs.title: Feature Selection - Testing for Independence
paragraphs.text:
%md

Feature selection is an important problem in Machine learning. There are many feature selection methods available such as mutual information, information gain, and chi square test.

The *threat* field will tell us if a measurement will tell us the threat level. We have many features (TransformerLoad, TopOilTemperature, etc.) but we are not
sure which features have an impact in *threat* class. Given a feature X, we can use Chi Square Test to evaluate its importance to distinguish the class. 

By calculating the Chi square scores for all the features, we can rank the features by the chi square scores, then choose the top ranked features for model training. In other words, 
the higher value of the \chi^2 score, the more likelihood the feature is correlated with the class, thus it should be selected for model training.

We will use Spark's ChiSqSelector to do this job for us and pick the right features for us automatically.

# 4 - Defining the Training Function

msg.data: 4 - Defining the Training Function

paragraphs.text:
%md

This training function will help us to train and export our models to PMML.

msg.data: This training function will help us to train and export our models to PMML.

paragraphs.title: 4.1 - Training Function
paragraphs.text:
%spark
    
def runPipelineOnData(fulldata: DataFrame, transformerCode: String, pipeline: Pipeline, PMMLClassNamePrefix: String) : Unit = {
    
    val data = fulldata.filter(col("Transformer")===transformerCode)
    
    val splits = data.randomSplit(Array(0.7, 0.3), 0)
    val trainingData = splits(0)
    val testingData = splits(1)
    
    val model = pipeline.fit(trainingData)
    
    val predictions = model.transform(testingData)

    val evaluator = new MulticlassClassificationEvaluator().setLabelCol("Threat")

    val accuracy = evaluator.evaluate(predictions)

    println("\t\tTest Error for Transformer " + transformerCode + " = " + (1.0 - accuracy) + "%")
    
    val fileName="/common_shared/pmml/IRISDemo.ImportedModel."+PMMLClassNamePrefix+transformerCode+".pmml"
    
    println("\t\tExporting the model to PMML file " + fileName)
    
    val file = new File(fileName)
    //val pmmlBuilder = new org.jpmml.sparkml.PMMLBuilder(fulldata.schema, model).build()
    
    val pmmlBuilder = new org.jpmml.sparkml.PMMLBuilder(fulldata.schema, model).buildFile(file)
    
}

## 5.1 - Creating the basic infrastructure

msg.data: 5.1 - Creating the basic infrastructure

paragraphs.text:
%spark

/*
I used to have "VibrationLevel" as an additional input col. But that would make the VectorIndexer build a translation from
a categorical value into an integer and that would appear as an additional feature on the model. That is not really a problem. 
The problem happens when we generate the PMML. This transformation to create this new artificial feature is exported into the PMML
as well and we still don't support that. I think we will support this pretty soon.
*/
val vectorAssembler = new VectorAssembler() 
    .setInputCols(Array("TransformerLoad", "TopOilTemperature", "BottomOilTemperature", "OilVolume", "MoistureInOil", "Vibration")) 
    .setOutputCol("rawFeatures")

val vectorIndexer = new VectorIndexer().setInputCol("rawFeatures").setOutputCol("features").setMaxCategories(4)

// This will take the top 3 most important features accordingly to Chi2
val selectorChi = new ChiSqSelector().setNumTopFeatures(4).setFeaturesCol("features").setOutputCol("selectedFeatures").setLabelCol("Threat")
